04645nam a22005415i 9780520940833DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209408337 a10.1525/97805209408332doi  a(DE-B1597)648753  a(OCoLC)1414456968  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aFrank, Ross, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Settler to Citizen :bNew Mexican Economic Development and the Creation of Vecino Society, 1750-1820 /cRoss Frank; ed. by Ross Frank. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (353 p.) :b12 figures, 19 b/w photographs, 9 maps, 5 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS AND TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ABOUT TRANSLATIONS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. "Like a Ball in the Hands of Fortune": New Mexican Economy through the 1770s -- tChapter 2. "If We Should Lose New Mexico a Second Time": Bourbon Reform, Indian Policy, and the Alliances of the 1780s -- tChapter 3. "This Type of Commerce Cannot Remedy Itself": Obstacles to Economic Growth in New Mexico and the Bourbon Response -- tChapter 4. New Mexican Economic Development, 1780-1820 -- tChapter 5. Creating Vecinos: Cultural Transformation -- tConclusion -- tNOTES -- tGLOSSARY OF COLONIAL SPANISH TERMS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe unique arts-and-crafts tradition of the American Southwest illuminates this economic and social history of colonial New Mexico, casting new light on the development of New Mexico's Hispanic community and its changing relationship with Pueblo Indians. Ross Frank's analysis of Pueblo Indian pottery, Pueblo and Spanish blankets, and Spanish religious images—or santos—links economic change to social and cultural change in this region. Using these cultural artifacts to gauge shifts in power and status, Frank charts the creation of a culturally innovative and dominating Hispanic settler—or vecino—community during the final decades of the eighteenth century. Contrary to previous views of this period as an economic backwater, Frank shows that Spanish New Mexico instead experienced growth that tied the region closely to colonial economic reforms of the Spanish empire. The resulting economic boom dramatically altered the balance of power between the Spanish settlers and the Pueblo Indians, giving the vecinos the incentive and the means to exploit their Pueblo Indian neighbors. Frank shows that the vecinos used different strategies to take control of the Pueblo textile and pottery trade. The Hispanic community began to define its cultural identity through the economic and social subordination of the Pueblo Indians. Connecting economic change to powerful cultural and social changes, Frank provides a new understanding of this "borderlands" region of northern New Spain in relatoin to the Spanish colonial history of Mexico. At the same time, From Settler to Citizen recovers the previously unexplored history of an important Hispanic community.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aFrank, Ross, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025159540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094083340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940833/original  a978-3-11-06904